cumulative
capacity
requirement (Am = 1) and maximum-safety-method (Em = 1) at capacity flexibility = 0.1. However, at capacity flexibility = 0.3, the costs increase compared to the combination of uncertainty-based
cumulative
capacity
requirement (Am = 1) and full-utilization-method (Em = 0). These observations closely align with the basic scenario analysed by Altendorfer et al. (2014), where the application of safety capacity at both, the estimation of capacity requirements and during the calculation of unbounded capacity provision, led to performance enhancements. However, unlike the findings in Altendorfer et al. (2014), the application of ConWIP demonstrates a higher performance increase when capacity flexibility increases, a phenomenon not observed in their study. We relate this performance enhancement to the restricted WIP within the production system, which is based on the ConWIP logic.
